%[text] %[text:anchor:T_453a] # Select LLC Resonant Converter Components and Controller
%[text] This script helps you select the rating of the primary inverter MOSFET, secondary rectifier diodes, and suitable controller parameters for the `LLCResonantConverterFullBridge` model.
%[text:tableOfContents]{"heading":"Table of Contents"}
%[text] ## Semiconductor Device Model
%[text] This design solution uses the Simscape™ MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) library block to model the primary MOSFET device, it provides two levels of model fidelity: thermal and non-thermal. The secondary diode is modeled using either the Simscape™ Foundation Library Diode block or the Simscape Electrical™ library Diode block, this also offering two fidelity levels.
%[text] To estimate switching losses and efficiency, the thermal variants of the MOSFET and tabulated diode blocks must be used. This configuration enables loss and temperature rise analysis of the converter.
%[text] Use the non-thermal variant of the MOSFET and the Foundation Library Diode block to tune the controller and analyze voltage and current across different components. This option gives faster simulation speeds and hence supports exploration of the design space better. To support easy switching between fidelity configurations, Simulink® subsystem reference models are used. You can modify the MOSFET and diode parameters within their respective subsystem reference models.
%[text] To open the non-thermal variant of the primary MOSFET subsystem reference model, at the MATLAB® Command Window, run:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCModelIdealMOSFETWithoutThermal");
%[text] ```
%[text] To open the thermal variant of the primary MOSFET subsystem reference model, at the MATLAB Command Window, run:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCModelIdealMOSFETWithThermal");
%[text] ```
%[text] To open the Simscape foundational library secondary diode subsystem reference model, at the MATLAB Command Window, run:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCModelBasicDiode");
%[text] ```
%[text] To open the Simscape electrical library tabulated secondary diode subsystem reference model, at the MATLAB Command Window, run:
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCModelTabulatedDiode");
%[text] ```
%[text] ## Select MOSFET and Diode Part
%[text] Select the primary MOSFETs and secondary diodes based on the voltage and peak current ratings required by your converter. Use the `SelectMOSFETRating` MATLAB® function to determine the appropriate device ratings. To simulate the primary inverter, use the Simscape MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) library block. To model zero-voltage switching (ZVS), add an external drain-to-source parasitic capacitor in parallel with the MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) block.
  %[control:button:1bcd]{"position":[1,2]}
if ~exist('LLCSpec', 'var');LLCConverterDefaultInputParameters; end % Loading the specification data
deviceRating = selectDeviceRating(LLCSpec,SafetyFactor = 1.2,NearestCurrentMultiplier=5,NearestVoltageMultiplier=10,... %[output:group:126ddfaf] %[output:2385574c]
    MagnetizingInductance=simscape.Value(LLCDesign.Lm,"H"),MinOperatingFreq=simscape.Value(frequencyRange.minFreq,"Hz")); %[output:group:126ddfaf] %[output:2385574c]
%[text] ### Parameterized MOSFET Subsystem
%[text] Based on the required ratings, you can either use existing parameterized MOSFET (Ideal, Switching) parts or parameterize the block using OEM datasheets and loss table XML files. In this design solution, pre-parameterized parts are used to select suitable MOSFETs and diodes. To select the appropriate MOSFET part, open the `LLCModelIdealMOSFETWithThermal` model. In the MOSFET block mask, launch the pre-parameterization manager by clicking the Select part button. Then, choose the MOSFET part that meets the required voltage and current ratings.
%[text] To open the parameterized MOSFET model, at the MATLAB Command Window, run: 
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCModelIdealMOSFETWithThermal.slx");
%[text] ```
%[text] 
%[text] ![](text:image:6e5c)
%[text] %[text:anchor:TMP_359b] To select the appropriate diode part, open the `LLCModelTabulatedDiode` model. In the Diode block mask, launch the pre-parameterization manager by clicking the Select part button. Then, choose the diode part that meets the required voltageand current ratings.
%[text] ![](text:image:1ef4)
%[text] ### LLC Controller
%[text] This design solution provides an LLC resonant converter controller subsystem with four controller options:
%[text] 1. 2P2Z compensator (Continuous S domain)
%[text] 2. 2P2Z compensator (Discrete Z domain)
%[text] 3. PI controller (Continuous)
%[text] 4. PI controller (Discrete) \
%[text] To open the LLC controller, at the MATLAB Command Window, run: 
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCResonantConverterFullBridge/Controller");
%[text] ```
%[text] ![](text:image:5745)
%[text] ### Tune Voltage Controller Parameters
%[text] The LLC resonant converter transfers energy at a fundamental frequency that is close to the switching frequency. Because the system time constant is also near the switching frequency, traditional average modeling techniques are not suitable for accurately capturing the converter dynamics. Instead, this design uses a time-domain simulation-based linearization approach with a sinestream disturbance. In this method, the converter is first simulated to reach steady-state at its operating point. Then, a series of small sinusoidal perturbations  at different frequencies are injected onto the switching frequency. By analyzing the system’s steady-state response to each sinusoidal input, the small-signal frequency response of the converter can be extracted directly from the simulation data. This technique accurately captures the essential dynamics of the system, including the effects of switching and resonance.
%[text] For output DC voltage control, a compensator with two poles and two zeros (2P2Z) is implemented. The compensator’s zeros are placed near the plant’s complex conjugate poles to improve dynamic response, and one of the compensator’s poles is used to cancel the ESR zero of the filter capacitor. The integrator coefficient is then chosen to give desired performance while also ensuring the desired phase and gain margins are achieved, ensuring robust closed-loop performance.
%[text] Compensator transfer function, $C\\left(s\\right)=K\_{\\textrm{vr}} \\frac{\\left(S+\\left(\\alpha +j\\beta \\;\\right)\\right)\\left(S+\\left(\\alpha -j\\beta \\;\\right)\\right)}{S\\;\\left(S+w\_{\\textrm{sr}} \\right)}\\;=\\;\\frac{K\_{\\textrm{vr}\\;} }{S}\\frac{\\left(\\frac{S^2 }{\\omega {\\;}\_z }+\\frac{S}{Q\_C \\omega {\\;}\_z }+1\\right)}{\\frac{S}{\\omega {\\;}\_{\\textrm{sr}} }+1}${"editStyle":"visual"} 
%[text] To design the compensator based controller,  at the MATLAB Command Window, run: 
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] edit 'LLCResonantConvertersControllerDesign'
%[text] ```
%%
%[text] ## LLC Resonant Converter Model
%[text] You can build the power converter model using your designed resonant tank, controller, parameterized MOSFETs, and diodes.
%[text] To open the parameterized LLC converter model, at the MATLAB Command Window, run: 
%[text] ```matlabCodeExample
%[text] open_system("LLCResonantConverterFullBridge");
%[text] ```
